{
  "answer": "**Manusmṛti 7.1** introduces *rājadharma* (Sanskrit: *rājadharmān pravakṣyāmi*), announcing the exposition of \"the Dharma of Kings\"—encompassing the origin, conduct, and soteriology of kingship as just administration (*daṇḍa*, punishment/order) and protection of the *varṇas* and *āśramas*.[^1]\n\nThe compound *rājadharma* fuses *rāja* (\"king\" or \"ruling\") with *dharma* (\"cosmic order, righteousness, duty proper to one's station\"), distilling the sovereign's vocation into the maintenance of social equilibrium via measured force.[^2] English \"duties of the king\" captures the functional aspect—rules for royal comportment—but smuggles modern bureaucratic connotations of mere administrative obligations, flattening *dharma*'s theological depth as normative order binding human action to divine sanction. A fuller gloss like \"law/righteousness of kingship\" better evokes how ch. 7 frames the king as a partial deity (*deva*), wielding *daṇḍa* to prevent anarchy (e.g., the strong devouring the weak like \"fish on a spit\").[^3]\n\n[^1]: Manusmṛti, ch. 7, [p-b46e87](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/07/translation/#p-b46e87).\n\n[^2]: Manusmṛti, ch. 7, [whole chapter](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/07/translation/).\n\n[^3]: Manusmṛti, ch. 7, [p-d56424](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/07/translation/#p-d56424).",
